title: For Sale:  vz 24 mauser
postcontent:
ivz 24 in good shape was issued to romania possibly used against russia in stalingrad 250.00
The Czechoslovakian Armaments Factory started making specially designated vz. 24s in 1938 after the German invasion. Romania was for a time part of the Axis during World War II. "Romanian" vz. 24s have a letter followed by an "R" in the serial number; for example SR 1XXX. Romanian vz. 24s "AR", "BR", "CR"... all the way through "YR" represent different periods of manufacturing, no rifle with "ZR" has been found. The Czechs made 25,000 rifles for each period roughly totaling 625,000 Romanian vz. 24s. Romanian vz. 24's saw action in Ukraine, Bessarabia, and Stalingrad in the hands of Romanian Soldiers fighting for the Axis. It was not until 1944 that Romania joined the Allies.

title: For Trade:  M92 Yugo Underfolder Krinkov Rifle in 7.62x39
postcontent:
Up for Trade is a NIB Yugo underforder M92 Krinkov in 7.62x39. Comes complete with Yugo cleaning kit, 30rd Yugo mag, Original Yugo short muzzle break (for SBR), sling, Yugo M92 original trigger pack, case and accessories carry pouch. These are very rare rifles. Krinkov Rifles are a factory short barreled AK47 with the short stroke system (10.5in barrel). They were designed and used by the Russian Speznaz for CQB. The extendend "hollow" muzzle brake has been put on with a tac-weld to make it legal length (16.25in).
     They are typically bought to SBR them as the extended muzzle break can be removed to install the short muzzle break after getting you SBR tax stamp. It was built on a proper Krinkov No-Dak Spuds underfolder lower receiver. 
     This is a brand new never fired Rifle still in the case! This is not a used parts de-milled kit..it is a brand new from the Yugo factory virgin rifle. 
     I can send more pictures upon request. You must be legal to own! 
     Typically an SBR version of this weapon sells for $2000 - $2500 + you still have to buy the $200 tax stamp.....this is the faster route and you can get the Tax Stamp at your leisure! I have two of these great firearms and am looking for a trade only at this time. Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Yugo Mauser M48 8mm, UNFIRED
postcontent:
This is a M48 Yugo Mauser in 8 mm manufactured between 1950-1952. It is a beautiful rifle that looks nearly factory new.  I have not even fired this rifle.  There is still cosmoline on the bolt.  See pictures for condition and let me know any questions.  Local sale Only.
The M48 Mauser is a post World War II Yugoslavian version of the Belgian Fabrique Nationale designed Mauser Model 1924 short rifle which was produced under contract by the "Kingdom of Yugoslavia" beginning in 1928 and ending with the Nazi occupation in 1941. After World War II, the Yugoslavs took this design and incorporated modifications based upon Germany's Mauser Karabiner 98k. Although similar in general appearance to that of the German rifle, many of the parts of these two rifles are not interchangeable, especially the bolt and related action parts. The main difference between the M48 and the K98k is that the M48 uses an intermediate-length receiver. They are usually easily identified by the top handguard, which extends behind the rear sight and ends just in front of the receiver ring, although this feature exists on other models as well.

In 1884, Swiss cutler Karl Elsener set up shop in Ibach-Schwyz, installing a waterwheel in Tobelbach Brook to run his grinding and polishing machines.
